  "routing": {
    "sender": "metaphysics-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "YES: Translator's Afterword, avoids spoilers, right structural place",
    "content": "**YES** — a Translator's Afterword. This is the structurally correct place for everything we've been struggling to include without spoiling the experiential sequences. After the reader has completed all eight essays, an Afterword can do what the Preface cannot: discuss the philosophical significance of the reversal mechanism, draw explicit connections to Kant, Husserl, Nagarjuna, and Wittgenstein, analyze how the author's framework relates to and departs from these traditions, and reflect on the translation process itself. This respects the author's own method — phenomena first, then the structures built upon them — by letting the reader have the experiences first and only then offering the scholarly apparatus for understanding them. A Translator's Afterword (rather than editor's or critical) is most appropriate because we are the ones who have worked most intimately with every sentence and can speak to both the philosophical content and the translation decisions with authority."
  }
}
